<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53052p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53052p">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53052p"> 52(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> vive la Pologne (C. Floquet) <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53052p"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Apr&egrave;s les exp&eacute;ditions de Crim&eacute;e, d&apos;Italie, de Chine et du Mexique, l&apos;Empire &eacute;tait officiellement, en 1867, &agrave; l&apos;apog&eacute;e de sa gloire, pendant l&apos;exposistion universelle que visitaient &agrave; l&apos;envi les souverains d&apos;Europe. C&apos;est &agrave; ce moment que M. Floquet, dont le chapeau fut d&eacute;sormais l&eacute;gendaire, s&apos;imposa &agrave; la post&eacute;rit&eacute;, en apostrophant l&apos;empereur de Russie de ces mots: <b>Vive la Pologne, Monsieur!</b> <br><font color="green">[TABLE DES MOTS]</font> 108: <mark>M. Floquet | Vive la Pologne, Monsieur!</mark> <small> E. Trogan, <a name="MHPF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MHPF"><cite title="source">Les Mots Historiques du Pays de France</cite></a> (1922) 79</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: According to the story, Charles Floquet was one of a crowd of barristers that cried out <i>Long live Poland!</i> on the occasion of the visit of Czar Alexander II to the Palais de Justice in Paris on 4 June 1867. </mm> </dd></dl>
